The LNL/LZR Project – Chronological Project History
1. The Beginning: Excel and Pure Observation 📊

The project did not start with a proof attempt. It began with a simple question:

Can the Collatz process be understood structurally instead of only computationally?

The first phase consisted almost entirely of Excel analyses. Large tables were created and extended from thousands to millions of numbers. The goal was not to prove Collatz directly, but to identify hidden regularities:

stopping times,
peaks,
trajectories,
parity patterns,
growth rates,
modulo classes,
and repeated structures.

At this stage, many hypotheses appeared promising and later failed.

2. The Poker Idea ♠️♥️♣️♦️

One of the earliest conceptual breakthroughs was the Poker Model.

The basic intuition was:

Poker has only finitely many starting hands.
Yet infinitely many games can arise.
Complex structures emerge from a finite rule set.

The question became:

Does Collatz also possess a finite "deck" of structural building blocks?

The project searched for:

number classes,
recurring combinations,
rankings,
and a "royal flush" among trajectories.

Although the poker analogy remained useful as intuition, it was eventually abandoned as a mathematical framework.

3. The Era of Abandoned Ideas 🚧

Many independent ideas were explored and later discarded.

Among them:

prime-factor approaches;
delta-2 and delta-4 theories;
mountain-generation hypotheses;
gravitational models;
parabolic boundaries;
mirror universes;
storage models;
DNA models based only on parity;
recursive decomposition schemes;
direct induction attempts.

Repeatedly, promising structures collapsed under larger tests.

Several times the project reached the conclusion:

"Perhaps Collatz cannot be attacked this way."

4. The "Give Up" Phase

After numerous failures, a central obstacle emerged:

The classical approach always seemed trapped in the same circle:

trajectories depend on peaks;
peaks depend on trajectories;
explanations became circular.

The project reached what later became known as the Henne–Ei Problem:

What comes first: the mountain or the path?

For some time, the possibility of abandoning the project entirely became real.

5. The Triple-Stem Model 🌳

The decisive change came with the introduction of the three-stem structure:

Left Stem (LS)

Generated by ordinary Collatz evolution:

n↦3n+1,n↦n/2
Right Stem (RS)

Generated independently from the powers of two:

1→2→4→8→16→⋯
Middle Stem (MS)

A new structure that becomes active only when both sides meet.

This changed the viewpoint completely:

The project no longer investigated isolated trajectories.

Instead, it investigated the geometry of collisions.

6. Solving the Chicken-and-Egg Problem 🥚🐔

The triple-stem idea led to a crucial insight:

A collision exists before it is confirmed.

The project formulated:

event time

=confirmation time

This produced the hypothesis:

the turning point already exists;
the system recognizes it only one operation later.

To formalize this delay, multiple synchronized systems were introduced:

LZS1;
LZS2;
LZS3.

The famous "chicken-and-egg problem" was reformulated as a problem of temporal offset.

7. The Discovery of Trajectories 🚗

Attention shifted from individual numbers to complete trajectories.

The project began to classify:

mountain structures;
valleys;
collision points;
turning points;
heights;
energy balances;
polygon chains.

The term LVR Trajectories emerged.

The main question became:

Why do all trajectories eventually collide with the right stem?

Large computational experiments up to extremely large search spaces followed.

8. Mountains, Peaks, and DNA 🧬

The project then introduced the idea that every natural number carries its own structural fingerprint:

DNA(n)

The DNA concept attempted to encode:

parity;
local structure;
admissible transitions;
key-lock behavior;
trajectory classes;
mountain topology.

This led to the construction of reproducible path codes for natural numbers.

