10. Key–Lock Structures 🔐

The project then moved toward the hypothesis that trajectories close because complementary structures fit together.

Ideas included:

keys;
locks;
ridges;
valleys;
blades;
notches;
mirrored path segments.

The conjecture became:

Every natural number possesses a reproducible key-lock code.

This resulted in the first public file:

"LZS Key Lock DNA Path Codes 1–100".

11. The Computational Engine ⚙️

To test the ideas, the project evolved from spreadsheets into software:

C++ implementations;
benchmark systems;
verification tools;
cache optimization;
opening books;
multi-width arithmetic;
reproducible tests.

The project became:

LNL/LZR

(Lange Number Line / Lange Calculation Engine).

12. Public Release 🚀

The project was eventually published as:

LNL/LZR Engine V2.0.0

The public release includes:

source code;
documentation;
benchmark reports;
project diary;
trajectory studies;
key-lock DNA codes;
proof framework.

The current scientific position is:

The project is not a completed proof of the Collatz conjecture.

Instead, it is an experimental research framework that attempts to understand Collatz through geometry, trajectories, activation rules, and structural decomposition.

And the search continues. 🔬🚀
